ACTION BLOCKS

There is now a bitfield on all living objects to use for restricting
their actions.  These should be used in all spells/powers/instances where
you wish to restrict the actions of another, and all abilities that would
be affected by a block such as these should check for it before allowing
the action.
Please note that the purpose of blocks is NOT to make a guild totally
ineffective.  You should be able to restrict enough powers to make a
character feel limited, yet leave enough powers untouched so that they
have some options remaining.

To use the defined block bits,
#include <blocks.h>
in your file.  Here are the defined blocks.

BLK_BLIND
This is for when a character can't see.  Looks, glances, searches and the
like should check for this.  Remember that sight is the most important
sense, and things that impose this restriction should be VERY rare.

BLK_CONCENTRATION
This will disrupt intense concentration.  Primarily this will ruin psionic
abilities, but perhaps some magical spells as well.  Examples might include
a swarm of tiny gnats that bite all over you or get into your ears and
buzz really loud.

BLK_ENTANGLE_ARMS
If you want to physically restrain a persons arms.  Primarily this will
ruin most fighting abilities, many thief abilities, and casting of spells
that require physical freedom to gesture or manipulate components.

BLK_ENTANGLE_LEGS
For when you want to physically restrain someone from moving.  Any physical
movement should check for this.

BLK_ENTANGLE
This is just a combination of the last two, so you can set them both at
once if you wish.

BLK_PARALYZE
When you want someone restrained magically or in some other nonphysical
way, use this rather than an entangle.

BLK_SILENCE
If this is set on a player, he cannot use abilities that depend on the
transmission of sound.  These include spellcasting that requires speech,
playing musical instruments, etc.  Use of this block on players by other
players should follow all the normal PK check rules.  

BLK_SILENCE_PK
// As of Dec 17 2003 this block will be phased out and
// BLK_HEARING should be used instead.
This block was intended to be the PK version of BLK_SILENCE but
was used instead for 'deafening' a player.

BLK_HEARING
Setting this block will stop a player from receiving normal
communication. The full range of effects will be determined
by the coders.


USING THE BLOCKS
These functions are defined for your use:
set_block(int);
Use this to set the block you want, using the definitions above.

remove_block(int);
Use this to remove a block, with the definitions given above.

query_block(int);
Check the status of any of the block bits, using the definitions above
as arguments.  With no arguments, the entire block field is returned.


